CHAPTER XVII\line\i\fs28 Trouble at Sea\i0\fs24\par
THE Hardys immediately recalled the incident of the missing Jack Wayne and his plane. Were Chet and Joe's attackers in some way connected with the hijacker?\par
Joe telephoned the local airport and spoke to a man there who knew the Hardys. The boy suggested that all pilots flying out at eleven be on guard against trouble. He also asked if there were any strangers in a private plane waiting to take off.\par
"There's no flight scheduled out of here at eleven, either commercial or private," he was told.\par
Joe contacted the two other nearby airports. A jetliner was leaving from the second, and every precaution would be taken. The Hardys waited at the Morton farm until noon, but no incident was reported from either field.\par
"Probably the message meant eleven o'clock tonight," Frank said, and called the airports again to renew the warning.\par
\i As \i0 the afternoon wore on and Mr. Hardy did not return, the boys gave up the idea of going to North Woods that day.\par
"What say we drive to the airports and do a little checking?" Frank suggested. Everything, however, was routine at the public airports. Nothing had been heard from Wayne or of his plane. And no ship had been chartered for a flight that evening. The boys came away disappointed.\par
By dinnertime Frank and Joe had reached the conclusion that if the remark had anything to do with a plane, it must be a private one that would take off at eleven, and probably from a private flying field.\par
Frank declared, "From what's happened so far -wallet, plane, that yacht blinking its lights off and on, and the wailing siren-I believe there might be something doing over the ocean. Suppose we wait out there tonight to find out."\par
Joe agreed. After dinner the boys told their mother and aunt of the proposed trip. Before Mrs. Hardy could express herself on the subject, Aunt Gertrude said excitedly:\par
"Take your two-way radio and keep in touch. If anybody bothers you, I'll give him a piece of my mind!"\par
The boys promised to take the set. Reluctantly Mrs. Hardy agreed to their going. Just before dark, they left for their boathouse, carrying binoculars as well as the radio. Joe unloosed the moorings and they shoved off.\par
The motor purred into action, but the young detectives decided on a trial spin before heading toward the open sea.\par
"She's okay," Frank called, after the boys had circled the bay a few times.\par
He guided the motorboat out of the inlet, which they had negotiated so perilously the evening of the storm. Tonight the ocean was as smooth as a new highway. Stars twinkled in the cloudless sky, but there was little light from the thin crescent moon.\par
"Oh, oh," Joe said presently. "We'd better not forget Aunt Gertrude." He pulled up the collapsible antenna and switched on the two-way radio. "Hello, Aunt Gertrude. Are you listening?" Then he turned the selector to hear her answer.\par
The receiver crackled with static, which was followed by a voice like an umpire calling a strike. "Listening! I've been waiting an hour. Where are you boys?"\par
"On a calm sea. Nothing to worry about."\par
The boys did not know whether what they heard was static or Aunt Gertrude snorting.\par
As Joe clicked off the set, he heard another motorboat and glanced back. He noticed moving red and green lights not far away.\par
"I'm afraid we're being followed!" he said to his brother.\par
Frank peered across their churning wake. The strange boat was gaining rapidly on them. He let out the throttle all the way, and the \i Sleuth \i0 leaped forward like a frightened rabbit.\par
For a few minutes it seemed as if it were putting distance between the two crafts. But the space gradually diminished. Joe turned on the radio.\par
"Aunt Gertrude, we think we're being followed by another boat. It's overtaking us. I'm going to hide the radio until we find out what's going on. Let you know later what happens."\par
He had barely collapsed the aerial and secreted the radio when the prow of a powerful speedboat pulled alongside them. Two men were in it.\par
"Stop!" one of them shouted.\par
Frank tried to get a good look at the strangers, but both of them wore hats pulled down low and collars turned up.\par
One of the men grabbed the side of the \i Sleuth \i0 and beamed a flashlight on the name plate. "Turn around and go back!" he commanded sharply.\par
"What for?" Joe said cheerfully. "Can't a couple of fellows have some fun?"\par
"You guys can have some fun ashore," the man sneered. "Do what I tell you, or else!"\par
"We're just out for a spin," Frank said as light-heartedly as he could under the conditions. "But we don't like being ordered to go home. Who are you, anyway?"\par
"It's not for kids to ask questions," said the man, vaulting into the Sleuth.\par
He was several inches over six feet and as burly as a bear. Menacingly he approached Joe.\par
"Are you going to scram?"\par
"No."\par
The man lunged at Joe, who tried to grapple with him. Frank sprang to his brother's defense, but before he could clamp a hold on the stranger, the assailant had pitched Joe far over the side of the boat. After a brief struggle Frank followed. The Hardys bobbed to the surface several feet from the boats.\par
Frank hissed into Joe's ear, "Pretend we can't swim."\par
The boys thrashed about madly, crying for help.\par
As the big man leaped back into his own boat, Joe heard him laugh and shout to his companion:\par
"That sure was easy. Let's go and report to the boss."\par
"Shall we take their boat in tow?" asked the other.\par
"The tide'll take care of that, pal," the big man shouted. "We've done what we were ordered to do. Let's scram!"\par
Frank and Joe forced themselves beneath the surface of the water several times, giving a genuine appearance of drowning. When the men saw this, they gave satisfied grunts and sped off.\par
By this time the lights of the bobbing \i Sleuth \i0 were farther away.\par
"We'll really have to swim for it," Frank said.\par
With steady, powerful strokes, the Hardys made for their drifting boat. They reached it together and hauled themselves over the side. Tumbling into the bottom, they lay still for a moment to catch their breath.\par
"We'd better turn off our lights," Frank said, reaching for the switch.\par
After everything had been quiet for several minutes, Joe reached for the radio and turned on the sender. In a hoarse whisper he said, "Aunt Gertrude, are you still there?"\par
"Yes," came the answer. "Frank! Joel Are you all right?"\par
When her nephew reported what had happened, Miss Hardy gasped.\par
"I knew something would happen. I was just about to send the police launch. Did those pirates leave?"\par
"Yes. We fooled 'em. As soon as we're sure they can't hear our engine, we're going farther out," Joe said, and switched off the set.\par
A few minutes later Frank started the motor and guided the Sleuth into deeper water. Not a ship was in sight, but a few minutes later they could just make out twinkling lights in the distance.\par
Joe pulled out the binoculars he had brought along. "It looks like the yacht we saw the night of the storm," he reported. "Listen!"\par
A siren was wailing! Its hollow, mournful sound crescendoed and wailed across the ocean.\par
Just as suddenly came the roar of a helicopter. Frank and Joe glanced at the Sleuth's clock. It was eleven-fifteen.\par
As the boys listened, the sound of the helicopter grew louder. The Hardys peered into the sky but could not see anything. Apparently the craft was traveling without lights.\par
"The same setup as the other night!" Frank cried excitedly.\par
"I see it!" Joe shouted.\par
The rotor blades twirled lazily as the craft came lower and lower.\par
"We'd better scram!" Joe cried out.\par
Frank was about to turn the Sleuth when the siren wailed again. To the boys' relief the helicopter moved off.\par
"I'll bet that was a signal," Frank said. "Do you suppose that ship . . . ?"\par
His question went unfinished as a flash of light came from the direction of the yacht. Then darkness again.\par
The helicopter was edging off in the direction of the ship. "That must have been a signal flare!"\par
"Let's go closer. Ill tell Aunt Gertrude what's going on," Joe said.\par
By mistake he clicked the receiving switch. Suddenly Miss Hardy's voice crackled over the radio.\par
"Boys, are you there? I have an important message-"\par
Joe switched to the sender. "Yes, we're here. Something's doing."\par
"Well, leave it and come home. Your father is back in town and wants you."\par
"We can't come now."\par
"There's been a burglary at a factory. Part of the money stolen from Chet was found there."\par
"Switch that off!" Frank commanded as he cut the Sleuth's motor.\par
He had observed a launch speeding toward them from the direction of the yacht.\par
"If it's those same men, we're sunk this time," Joe said, hiding the radio once again.\par
The boys counted on the darkness to conceal the Sleuth. There was a bright light on the yacht now. The helicopter was directly over it. A wire ladder dangled from the chopper. A man was descending it.\par
"Great crow!" Joe exclaimed. "I'll bet the wallet we found was dropped from that helicopter!"\par
"Get down!" Frank warned as Joe craned his neck to see better.\par
He ducked to the floor of the Sleuth just as the launch's searchlight swept across it. Before it swung back, the Hardys had covered themselves with tarpaulin to avoid detection. The light was trained steadily on the Sleuth as the other boat rushed toward it.\par
There came the sound of a loud splash. It was followed by a string of oaths from the boat, which was now almost beside the Sleuth.\par
A muffled voice from the boat gave them a clue. "There goes five thousand dollars. The boss'll pin somebody's ears back for this."\par
"For ten grand I wouldn't be in that guy's shoes," came a gruff reply. "Bad enough to lose that wallet. Well, let's take a look at that boat."\par
Through a crack in the tarpaulin Joe could see that the rays of the launch's searchlight were probing every corner of the Sleuth for signs of life.\par
"Just a driftin' boat. Prob'ly the one those kids had who got drowned. Yep, this is it-the Sleuth."\par
At that moment a wailing sound filled the air.\par
"There's the siren," the gruff voice said. "We ain't got much time."\par
"I'm goin' to hop in and take a look, anyhow," the persistent fellow replied. "I might find some-thin' worth takin'."\par
"I ain't so sure. Last time we hit port, Renny-"\par
"Shut up! I'm goin' to take a look."\par
The Hardys felt the Sleuth lurch as one of the men leaped over the side.\par
The boys held their breath, fearful that even the pounding of their hearts might be heard.\par
"Hey! I found a radio-one of them two-way jobs," the man said. "I'll see if it works."\par
He clicked it on. The next instant a woman's voice cried out clearly:\par
"This is Aunt Gertrude. Frank and Joe Hardy, why don't you answer me? Do you need any help?"\par
The man shut the set off and gave a low laugh. "Well, Mr. Hardy, tell Aunt Gertrude for me they've gone to Davy Jones's locker."\par
There was a loud, coarse guffaw. "Bring that radio! Maybe we'll hear something from the big dick himself. He's getting too hot."\par
The man handed the radio across the water. The \i Sleuth \i0 swayed as he took a long step backward. His foot planted itself squarely upon Frank's back!\par
