\fs20 CHAPTER XVIII\fs24\line\b\i\fs28 Caught!\i0\par
\b0\fs24 INSTINCTIVELY Frank let out a stifled gasp as the intruder's heel dug into his ribs.\par
The tarpaulin covering was ripped off. A hairy sailor towered over him.\par
"Ha!" the man shouted in anger. "One of the Hardy boys! Jeff was wrong. You didn't drown!"\par
He reached down, grasped Frank's shirt front, and pulled the boy to his feet.\par
"I'll knock you cold before I toss you over. Then you won't never come back to life!" he threatened.\par
Frank watched. As the big fellow cocked his arm, the youth caught a glimpse of Joe peeling off the canvas covering and rising behind the burly thug.\par
The man in the launch saw the move, too. "There's another kid!" he shouted.\par
His warning came too late. Before the ham-like fist could start its forward journey, Frank, with the agility of a tiger, delivered a shove to his assailant's mid-section. As the man teetered, Joe flung a crushing body block against the back of his legs.\par
The sailor keeled over like a falling tree, his head cracking against the gunwale. He rolled over on his face, moaned, and lay still on the bottom of the \i Sleuth.\i0\par
So swiftly had the blow been struck that the man in the launch stared, speechless. He reached toward the dashboard and pressed a button. Then, letting out a shrill yell, he made a flying leap for the Hardys. He landed in the \i Sleuth \i0 simultaneously with a rumbling noise that quickly rose to a wail.\par
"He's set off a siren!" Joe cried out.\par
Frank plunged into the fellow, knocking him on top of his henchman. Joe flung himself into the melee, and together the boys pinned him down.\par
Above the din they heard another siren. "The yacht's answering!" Frank cried.\par
The prisoner beneath the boys snarled and puffed.\par
"Save your strength," Frank retorted. "You'll need it for the swim back."\par
"Let's tie him up and take him with us," Joe suggested. "That'll make two prisoners who may be able to help us solve the riddle of the wailing siren."\par
"No." Frank said. "Carrying both of them will make too much weight for the \i Sleuth. \i0 We're going to have to run for it and we'll need every bit of speed. I think our one prisoner will tell plenty."\par
From across the water a speedboat churned rapidly in their direction.\par
"Here you go, sailor!" Frank said.\par
The boys lifted the struggling man over the side of the \i Sleuth. \i0 He hit the water with a flat splash. Spluttering, he started swimming toward the launch, which had drifted some yards away.\par
Instantly Joe took the wheel and started the \i Sleuth's \i0 engine. As it leaped into action, Frank yanked a life jacket from a locker. Bending over their prisoner, he thrust the man's limp arms into it and buckled the straps.\par
"What are you doing?" Joe shouted.\par
"This fellow may have to be our secret weapon," Frank replied.\par
"How?"\par
Before Frank could explain, the searchlight from the launch suddenly started to move across the water. The sailor had reached his own boat, climbed in, and was after them!\par
"Great crow!" Joe exclaimed. "We can't make it, Frank, with two boats after us!"\par
"Don't be too sure."\par
Frank kept a wary eye on the unconscious man beside him, at the same time listening to the racing motor of the \i Sleuth. \i0 His insistence upon perfection in its engine was paying dividends. Joe made a beeline for the inlet. Although they were outdistancing the launch, the speedboat was creeping up. Suddenly there was a shot.\par
"They're firing on us!" Joe shouted.\par
Their prisoner began to revive. He twisted from side to side, mumbling. Frank could catch nothing intelligible. It sounded like \i crack-gun -crack.\i0\par
Frank watched the man carefully to remain master of the situation. He felt in the captive's pockets for weapons, or something that might identify him with the gang of smugglers or kidnappers. He found nothing.\par
"If the guy in the speedboat gets too close, I'm going to turn around and ram him!" Joe cried.\par
"You won't have to."\par
"How the dickens are we going to beat him? Look at him gain on us!"\par
"There's your answer!" Frank pointed to their prisoner. As the speedboat raced to head off the \i Sleuth \i0 before she could make the narrow inlet, he shouted, "Now's the time!"\par
He helped the life-jacketed man to his feet. "You okay?" he asked.\par
"Sure. Why-?" The sailor suddenly realized what was about to happen. His fist shot out.\par
But Frank was ready for him. He dodged, caught the sailor off balance, and pushed him into the sea.\par
"Now's our chancel" he shouted. "Run for it, Joe!"\par
Over the roar of the motor the boys heard a shout. Immediately the speedboat throttled down and came alongside the swimming sailor. At the same moment, the launch made a quick turn and barely avoided running down the man in the water. The boys could hear the engine going into reverse.\par
Joe urged the Sleuth to its top speed and grinned at his brother. "Your secret weapon worked swell!"\par
But the man in the launch did not give up the chase. After standing by to see that the sailor was picked up, he renewed the pursuit. The gun went into action again, and the boys crouched low. Bullet after bullet sang over their heads or spat into the waves. Joe was zigzagging the Sleuth's course.\par
"He's really pouring it on," Joe said grimly.\par
"Gosh, if we only had our radio, Joe, we could have told Aunt Gertrude to notify the Coast Guard."\par
Again the launch was gaining on them. The speedboat had turned back toward the dim hulk of the yacht.\par
"If we can only make the bay," Frank thought, "I know of plenty of places to hide where the water's shallow and that launch can't follow us."\par
"Here-we-are!" Joe shouted.\par
He applied a stiff left rudder. The \i\fs27 Sleuth \i0\fs24 took the turn like a champion and sped through the mouth of Barmet Bay.\par
A snug cove lay a quarter of a mile ahead. The racing \i Sleuth \i0 reached it and turned in. There was no sign of the pursuing launch.\par
"We lost them!" Joe cried in relief. "I thought they had us! Too bad about our prisoner. He might have told us plenty."\par
"He didn't have a thing in his pockets," said Frank. "And besides, he probably wouldn't have talked. We'd better phone the Coast Guard pronto."\par
Joe docked at an all-night waterfront restaurant in the inlet. Frank jumped out and rushed for a pay phone. When he had finished his detailed report, the lieutenant said, "We'll dispatch a boat at once to look for the speedboat and the launch. And I'll notify our stations along the coast to go after that yacht and also check on the helicopter. I'll get in touch with Police Chief Collig too."\par
A few minutes later Joe guided the \i Sleuth \i0 to their boathouse. When the brothers arrived home, the Hardy house was brightly lighted and alive with excitement.\par
"It's you! Thank goodness!" Aunt Gertrude exclaimed.\par
Briefly Frank and Joe told what had happened to them. In turn they asked for particulars about the burglars at the factory, and whether their father had reported anything further.\par
"No," Mrs. Hardy answered. "You're to stand by until he calls. In the meantime you'd better get to bed."\par
As the boys were putting on pajamas a little later, Frank said he thought the house should be guarded.\par
"That gang may still try something desperate -and before morning." He slipped into slacks and moccasins. "I'm going downstairs," he said.\par
"I'll take a turn later," Joe told him. "But call me if you hear anything."\par
It was nearly two o'clock when Frank halted at a side window that looked out on the driveway. As he peered through the narrow space, he drew back quickly. Was it an illusion, or did he detect a motion in the bushes beside the garage?\par
Every muscle in the boy's body tensed as he watched. The bushes parted and a man looked out. The dark figure stood motionless as if to listen, then made a "come-on" motion with his hand. Immediately the bushes parted again and a second figure emerged from the shadows. Together they tiptoed toward the house, hugging the shadows.\par
Frank raced upstairs to summon Joe. The younger boy, rousing instantly, hopped into slacks and loafers and hastened to the first floor.\par
"There they are!" Frank whispered, pointing to the space below the shade of the side window. "They're coming to the back door."\par
"They can't open it."\par
"I unlocked it. We'll jump 'em."\par
"Good strategy."\par
The boys tiptoed into the kitchen and stood behind the door. Soon they heard a low voice say:\par
"We can't fail this time. We've got to get Hardy's reports . . ."\par
"We'll try the door, then one of the windows." The knob turned. "What do you know? They left this door unlocked."\par
The door opened slowly.\par
"Okay!" came a hoarse whisper. "This way. Don't make a sound. And watch out for the two boys."\par
As a dark figure appeared in the doorway, Joe charged like a young bull, hitting the intruder a solid blow and tumbling him onto the porch.\par
Frank followed with a flying tackle in the direction of the second man, but missed him. He dashed off through the yard and vaulted the hedge. Frank went after him.\par
Joe was still grappling with the man on the porch. The struggling prisoner suddenly jack-knifed his knees and was about to deliver a vicious kick at the boy's head when the porch light went on and a voice shouted:\par
"Don't you dare!"\par
A rush of footsteps was instantly followed by a sharp blow, and the man went limp as an empty glove. Joe jumped up.\par
The light from the kitchen revealed Aunt Gertrude, her brother's hickory stick in her right hand, standing over the prone figure.\par
"Try to harm my nephew, will you?" she said, waving the cane menacingly.\par
As the man moaned and tried to sit up, Joe gasped. The fellow was tall and had red hair!\par
"You!" the boy cried out. "The man who knocked out my friend Chet and me and took our two thousand dollars!"\par
The prisoner glared. "I don't know what you're talkin' about," he muttered weakly.\par
"Oh, yes, you do," Joe said. Aunt Gertrude handed him a rope and he bound the intruder's arms and legs. "You're one of the gang my father's after. You're smuggling rifles out of this country."\par
For an instant there was a look of guilty surprise on the man's face, then he denied ever having heard of such a thing.\par
By this time Mrs. Hardy had arrived on the scene, and suggested they go inside the house.\par
"This is all a mistake, lady!" the prisoner pleaded.\par
"We'll let the police decide that."\par
Before they could telephone headquarters, Frank came rushing into the house. "You've got him!" he cried, seeing the prisoner. "That practically proves we have the right car!"\par
"What car?" Joe asked.\par
Frank explained that when he chased the red-haired man's companion along the street back of the Hardys', the fellow had started to cross over to a parked car. He had changed his mind when two policemen loomed up beside it, and he had sped on.\par
"Was he caught?"\par
"No. He was too quick for Smuff and Riley and me."\par
"Smuff and Riley?"\par
Frank nodded. "They were given this beat to patrol, and actually found a blue car with a scratch on the door. It fits the description of the one parked near Chet's farm."\par
The prisoner's jaw opened in astonishment. Frank went on, "If he won't tell us who he is, the motor vehicle department will."\par
"It's not my car!" the man cried out. "It belongs to . . ." Suddenly he realized he had said too much, and from then on kept sullenly silent.\par
"Where are Smuff and Riley?" Aunt Gertrude asked. "Bring them here to take this-this cutthroat away!"\par
Officer Riley came in, puffing from the exertion of pushing the car around the corner. Smuff was guarding it at the curb.\par
"A prisoner, eh?" Riley beamed. "You sure got him tied up for delivery." He laughed at his own joke. "Well, I'll take him to headquarters."\par
"Just a minute," Frank said. "I believe the rest of the gang may have been brought in by the Coast Guard. I'll make a phone call."\par
He went to the hall telephone and spoke to the lieutenant, first telling him of the red-haired man's capture, then asking if the launch or speedboat or yacht had been boarded.\par
The officer said his men had returned empty-handed. The suspected craft had too much of a head start. He assured Frank, however, that a plane would be sent out at daybreak to check on the yacht.\par
Frank hung up, but stayed at the telephone. In a loud voice he said excitedly, "Oh, that's just great, Lieutenant! Now our prisoner will certainly talk!"\par
He returned to the kitchen. Continuing his hoax, he said to their captive, "Quite a racket you fellows were carrying on. How did you ever get tangled up in such a dangerous business? Uncle Sam has taken a hand in it now!"\par
The man glowered, but remained silent.\par
Both Frank and Joe tried to force a further confession from him, but he remained obdurate. Finally Frank said:\par
"We may as well turn you over to the police. They have ways of making people talk. Riley, how about calling headquarters for a car to take this guy down?"\par
"Sure thing, Frank," the officer assented.\par
"Then I'll go outside and tell Smuff what's happened." He went to the telephone. While he was gone, Joe said:\par
"I wish we could keep our prisoner here until we hear from Dad."\par
The man greeted these words with an evil snort.\par
"Your dad, eh? Fenton Hardy! I knew we'd get around to that."\par
"What do you mean?"\par
"Listen here. If you promise to let me go, I might be able to make a little deal with you folks."\par
"We don't go for deals," Joe said. "But what's on your mind?"\par
"It's simple. In exchange for my freedom I'll give you some important information. I'll tell you where they're holding your father!"\par
\par
CHAPTER XIX\line\b\i\fs28 Danger in North Woods\b0\i0\fs24\par
"DAD captured?" Joe shouted in disbelief.\par
The man nodded, smiling evilly. Mrs. Hardy turned white, and Aunt Gertrude put an arm about her.\par
"How do we know you're not lying?" Joe asked evenly.\par
The man shrugged. "That's up to you."\par
The Hardys moved out of earshot of the criminal for a whispered conference. All agreed that the story of the factory theft might have been a means of luring the detective into a trap.\par
"We'll check on this burglary," Joe said. "Where was it?"\par
"In Hambleton at the airplane motors factory."\par
"I'll call the police." Joe hurried upstairs to his father's study. But neither the local nor State Police had heard of the theft. Joe came downstairs and relayed the news to his family.\par
"I can't believe Dad would walk into a trap that easily," said Frank. "Wait a minute. I want to look for something in his files."\par
He went to the study and unlocked Fenton Hardy's filing cabinet, which he had permission to do in case of emergency.\par
Thumbing through the files, Frank noted that Mr. Hardy was under contract to direct plant security work at the Hambleton company where secret government work was being carried on.\par
The name and private number of the company's president were listed. Frank quickly dialed.\par
Mr. Hartwick answered. When Frank had convinced him of his identity, Mr. Hartwick said:\par
"Yes, Frank. There has been a burglary here. We're keeping it secret to tackle the problem from the inside first."\par
"Is Dad all right?"\par
"Yes, so far as I know. He's out here now."\par
"Will you find him and have him phone home? Something important has come up here."\par
As Frank hurried down the stairs he heard scuffling in the kitchen. The redheaded man was trying desperately to get away.\par
"Your trick didn't work," Frank announced. "I know where my father is."\par
Frank told the others that Mr. Hardy was safe. Just then the telephone rang. Moments later Frank heard the calm voice of his father at the other end of the line.\par
Frank quickly told all that had happened to them on the ocean and later. Fenton Hardy listened in amazement. When the boy had finished, the detective said:\par
"You boys have done a great job. Now there are two things I want you to do. Try to find out something about the helicopter. And meet me here at noon."\par
"Yes, Dad."\par
As Frank said good-by, a prowl car stopped in front of the house. Two policemen jumped out and hustled the prisoner into the car.\par
The Hardy home became quiet once more as the four occupants retired for some much-needed sleep. Frank and Joe did not awaken until nine o'clock. As soon as they were dressed, Joe telephoned the Coast Guard. After a long conversation he hung up.\par
"The Coast Guard's flying boat located the yacht," he told Frank.\par
"Did they stop it?"\par
"Landed alongside arid boarded her."\par
"What did they find?"\par
"Nothing! Everything was in order and the captain, named Haxon, denied any connection with a helicopter. If the yacht was carrying smuggled goods, the captain probably got scared and ordered it dumped overboard. Anyway, the plane's keeping an eye on the yacht as she goes down the coast."\par
A desperate effort to find a trace of the helicopter drew a blank.\par
"It's a private helicopter-very private," Joe concluded. "And flies only at night. But we'll find it, just as soon as this burglary business is settled."\par
At eleven-thirty the boys started out to meet their father. The factory was surrounded by a high wire fence. As Frank drove up to the main gate, he was stopped by a uniformed guard.\par
The guard studied the boys' identifications for a moment. "Okay," he said. "We've been waiting for you."\par
The brothers were soon ushered into Mr. Hart-wick's office. Their father and the company president were seated at a desk, minutely examining something with a magnifying glass.\par
"Hello, boys," the detective greeted them. "Mr. Hartwick, I want you to meet Frank and Joe, my two assistants."\par
The boys shook hands with him, and the detective continued. "Burglars broke into this plant last night and stole a quantity of secret airplane gadgets being made for use in United States military planes. As they left, one of them dropped this."\par
He held up a twenty-dollar bill. "Ever see this before?" He handed the money over.\par
Frank looked at the serial number, comparing it with the list in his wallet. "I'll say so! This is one of the bills I gave to Chet."\par
"Just as I figured," the detective said. "Either the extortionists and the burglars are the same people, or they're associated in some way. Boys, I want you to do something for me."\par
"Yes, Dad?"\par
"Tour this plant as if you were on an inspection trip of some kind. Keep your eyes open for that phony salesman you saw at Chet's farm, or anybody else you've caught a glimpse of in this mystery. We think one or more of the gang we're after may be working right here."\par
Guided by a junior executive, the boys went from one department to another, but nobody answered the description of any of the suspects. Frank and Joe were completing the tour in the packing department when Joe stopped short and pointed.\par
"Frank, look at that engine over there!"\par
"That's just like the one we saw in the shack in the woods!" his brother said in a low voice.\par
The boys hastened back to their father and voiced their suspicions. The detective looked at Mr. Hartwick. "Have you missed any motors?"\par
"Several," Mr. Hartwick replied. "But we thought they were lost by the trucking company. We've sent through a tracer but haven't heard a thing yet."\par
The Hardys were convinced the motors had been stolen and hidden in North Woods.\par
"We won't put off our trip to the woods any longer," the boys' father said. "I only hope those suspects haven't moved out."\par
The company president thanked the Hardys for their help and they left the factory. They arrived home to find Aunt Gertrude standing on the front steps, an envelope in her hands.\par
"A state trooper brought this a second ago," she said. "It's for you, Fenton,"\par
Mr. Hardy opened the envelope, his eyes taking on a look of satisfaction as he read the enclosure. "Even better than I thought," he said, explaining that he had asked for a list of any recent factory thefts along the Atlantic seaboard. "This note says there have been thefts in five airplane and three rifle manufacturing plants. The thing to do now is fit the pieces of this puzzle together."\par
After a hasty luncheon, Mr. Hardy asked his sons to come to his study. Reaching into his gun case, he pulled out two pistols.\par
"Take these. You may need them if the wolves attack. I'll make out the appropriate permits for you to carry them. We're on a dangerous mission."\par
"Dad, do you think these thefts of airplane parts and rifles are tied up with the mystery of the wailing siren?" Frank asked.\par
"Yes. I'm sure they're being shipped out of the country "on that yacht."\par
"With the help of the helicopter?" Joe asked excitedly.\par
"That's what we have to prove. It may be a difficult matter to locate the helicopter. But the clues you boys have picked up seem to tie together neatly," Mr. Hardy said admiringly.\par
He checked his own pistol, then picked up a peculiar-looking weapon, which he put into a shoulder holster.\par
"This is a special gun," he said. "It doesn't kill -just shoots a gas that acts as an anesthetic."\par
With admonitions from Mrs. Hardy and Aunt Gertrude to be careful, the three hurried to the boys' car. Frank took the wheel and drove to the trail which the campers had taken. With Joe in the lead, they started off through the woods.\par
Upon reaching the brook, they crossed it and went in a straight line toward the wolf-man's cabin.\par
The Hardys pressed quickly and silently through the dense woodland for half an hour. Suddenly they became aware of distant howls.\par
"The wolves!" Joe said.\par
"They've picked up our scent!" Frank cried out.\par
The boys loaded their pistols. Mr. Hardy led the way, halting suddenly behind a thorny bush.\par
"The wire stockade!" Joe whispered.\par
Before them was the enclosure, from which came the howling of the excited wolves.\par
Mr. Hardy took out his shoulder gun. "Temporary sleep won't harm these beasts!" he said.\par
"While I'm giving them a taste of this gas, you boys see if their owner's at home and keep him busy till I show up."\par
As the detective crept forward through the heavy brush, Frank and Joe angled off in the direction of the cabin. When they had almost reached it, they halted.\par
Before them, framed in the dark doorway, stood the bearded wolf-man. He stepped out, quickly followed by another man, who was small, stooped, and unshaven. When they saw the boys, both men stopped short.\par
"I thought I told you trespassers to stay away from here!" the wolves' owner shouted at them angrily.\par
"We'd like to talk to you," Frank said.\par
The smaller man grinned at his companion through two broken teeth. "Who are they, Krack? Friends of yours?"\par
\i Krack! \i0 Another piece of the puzzle suddenly dropped into place. The man from the launch had mumbled \i Krack-gun-Krack!\i0\par
"The only things that talk around here are the wolves," Krack said cuttingly. He motioned with his hand. "Come here, Saber!"\par
At his command, the wolf stalked through the doorway. It eyed the boys savagely, whining for his master to give the word and he would be at their throats.\par
The boys thrust their hands into their pockets.\par
The pistols were ready. They would use them only in case . . .\par
Suddenly Saber pricked up his ears. Krack took notice.\par
"There's somebody at the stockade, Jezro!" he cried out. Then he bellowed at the wolf. "Stockade, Saber! Kill!"\par
Gooseflesh rose on the Hardy boys as the brute dashed toward the stockade. They had forgotten to warn their father about this killer!\par
\par
CHAPTER XX\line\b\i\fs28 A Surprise Capture\i0\par
\b0\fs24 THE Hardy boys stared in horror as the wolf bounded toward the stockade.\par
They raced after it, pistols poised to shoot if they could sight the animal. Suddenly, from near the cage, came the report of a gun. There was a yelp of pain, then complete silence.\par
When Frank and Joe reached the clearing, their father was not in sight. The caged wolves lay in a stupor. Saber was dead.\par
Krack and Jezro arrived on the heels of the boys. They stared transfixed at the sight. Then Jezro gave a crazy laugh and dashed off among the trees.\par
"Come back here!" Krack cried out.\par
"I'm gettin' out of here and you've got no wolves to stop me!" Jezro flung back.\par
A bullet from Krack's gun hissed through the trees.\par
"We'd better go before he aims that thing at us," Frank advised. "He'll get wise in a minute that we're mixed up in this."\par
"You bet. Let's follow Jezro. Maybe he'll spill what he knows."\par
Out of range of Krack, Frank and Joe took off after Jezro. The man's speed proved no match for the fleet-footed Hardys.\par
Joe leaped upon his back, bringing the scrawny man to the ground. Frank collared him and raised the fugitive to a sitting position.\par
"Lemme go!" he whined. "Maybe them wolves ain't dead."\par
"I can guarantee they'll take a long sleep," Frank said. "Now, what's going on here?"\par
Jezro remained silent.\par
"All right. If you won't talk, we'll tell you a few things. You stole a truck with rifles and hardware and camping equipment, and brought it here."\par
"No, I didn't. It was Red Mike. He's daffy over campin' stuff. I never leave these woods."\par
"Does your friend Mike have red hair?" Frank asked.\par
"Yeah. How'd you know?"\par
"We caught him. He's in jail."\par
Now thoroughly frightened, Jezro told the boys he was a wanted thief, who had met Krack while hiding out in the tumble-down shack in the woods.\par
"He got me to work with him and his friends,"\par
Jezro said. "Promised me big money to help 'em keep people out o' the woods."\par
"Where were you when we came to the woods before?" Joe prodded him.\par
"Following you. I was spyin' on you when you found Mike's canoe."\par
"Our canoe," Frank corrected. "Go on."\par
"Mike and Trippek were in Wells Hardware buying a new fish pole the day your fat friend was there," Jezro said. "That boy sure was giving everybody an earful about his uncle's rifles. So right then and there Mike decided to swipe the truck and take everything in it."\par
"Who's Trippek?" Frank interrupted.\par
"Tall, blond fellow."\par
"Sells insect repellent?"\par
"He did once so he could find out about you fellows. Then I watched you guys when you came here. I marked those trees to make the trail." He laughed. "It got you out of the way, easy enough."\par
"I suppose you dug the pit to trap us," Frank said.\par
"No. Krack did. He didn't want nobody prowlin' around the woods. Listen here. You ought to let me go. I done you a favor. I left you a note tellin' you it was dangerous here."\par
Joe gave Frank a wink. "Do you believe that? Crooks hang together. Jezro wouldn't squeal on Krack."\par
"Oh, wouldn't I? Listen, boys, I'm a thief, but I don't steal things to help people make war on their own country!"\par
Before Frank could ask Jezro to explain his startling remark, the sound of a wailing siren filled the woods. Joe looked into the sky, half expecting to see a helicopter.\par
"That's from the cabin," Jezro said. "Krack's warnin' the other men."\par
Frank realized that if Krack's henchmen were near, the boys would have to hurry to uncover the loot they were seeking.\par
"Where are they hiding the stolen stuff, Jezro?" he asked sharply.\par
"I'll tell you, but you gotta let me go if I do."\par
"We won't hurt you," Joe said. "But don't try to get away, or it'll go hard with you."\par
Jezro nodded and led the boys into a thicket. After he had gone a hundred yards he stopped.\par
"The stuff's hidden in there," he said, pointing to a dense copse.\par
"I'll take a look," Frank told his brother. "You guard Jezro."\par
Frank made his way cautiously. Presently he came to an extensive clearing over which was stretched a green canvas with bushes and branches laid here and there upon it. Pulling up one edge of the camouflage, Frank uncovered a row of lights, set along the ground.\par
"Jeepers!" he exclaimed half-aloud. "A landing field for the helicopter."\par
The solution to the wailing siren mystery was becoming clear. Stolen plane parts, engines, arms, and ammunition were being hidden in the wilderness. They were picked up by the helicopter at night and carried out to sea, where they were secretly loaded onto the yacht.\par
"The wailing siren is used to announce its comings and goings," Frank concluded. "I wonder where the helicopter is now."\par
Frank searched a little longer, but could find none of the equipment stolen from Chet. He hurried back to make Jezro reveal the spot. As he reached him and Joe, he noticed some bushes moving just ahead. Before he could shout a warning, three men, pistols in hand, jumped out of concealment.\par
"Reach for the clouds!" one of them snapped. He had blond hair and a voice that was familiar. Trippek!\par
"Frisk 'em, men, and tie 'em up," came an order from a small dark man with a limp. He was Rainy Night, the man who had left the note at the newspaper office and later had helped steal the Hardys' money from Chet.\par
He turned to Jezro. "As for you, you traitor, you'll get the same treatment."\par
"Please, Renny, don't do this to me!" Jezro wailed. "I ain't told 'em nothin'."\par
The dark-haired man sneered. "Think that over while you're starving to death. You and your two pals here!"\par
The men pulled several long pieces of wire from their pockets. Standing the Hardys and Jezro against a tree, they bound them fast to the trunk.\par
Trippek chuckled. "Haxon would get a kick out of this!" he said.\par
Haxon! Frank and Joe looked at each other. The captain of the yacht!\par
At that moment Krack came striding out of the woods. He shot a contemptuous glance at Jezro and the boys.\par
"Please, please," Jezro begged. "I was only foolin'."\par
"Shut up! I'll deal with you later." Krack turned toward the other men. "Bad luck. That's all we've had since these brats started spying on us."\par
"Better not talk here," Trippek advised.\par
Krack jerked a thumb toward the boys. "They're as good as finished, so it won't hurt if they listen in."\par
"What's up?" Trippek asked, worried.\par
"The yacht's been boarded. Haxon sent me the message short wave."\par
"Did they dump the load?"\par
"Just in time. Haxon said one motor accidentally fell into the ocean from the copter. The Coast Guard, even with the evidence destroyed, will keep an eye on Haxon and the yacht."\par
"What's the caper now?" one of the others asked.\par
"To move. I wish we had brought the copter back here."\par
"Where is it?"\par
"In the barn at Beekman's farm."\par
The boys knew the secluded place on the outskirts of North Woods. It had been abandoned a long time and would serve as a perfect hiding place.\par
"We'll keep Fenton Hardy there until the heat is off," Krack said, looking at the boys.\par
The boys were startled, but remembering the trick their prisoner Red Mike had tried to play at the Hardy house, Frank said, "You'll not catch Dad."\par
Krack laughed. "Oh no? We have him now. Caught him near the wolf pen."\par
"You're bluffing," Joe said.\par
Krack pulled Mr. Hardy's gas gun from his belt. "Recognize this? If it had another load of gas in it, I'd let you have it."\par
Perspiration broke out on the boys' foreheads. With their father captured, the outlook appeared bleak indeed. Nevertheless, Joe defiantly reminded Krack that the police would soon catch up with them.\par
"Thanks for reminding me of the police," Krack said with a sneer. "Men, I'll open the wolves' pen. They'll be awake soon. If the cops come, they'll get theirs. We'll stay in the caves while the wolves take care of 'em."\par
In the conversation that followed, Frank and Joe learned an amazing story of foreign intrigue which was being conducted by Renny, alias Rainy Night, whose real name was Renaldo. These men were working for a large unscrupulous foreign combine which had planned uprisings in Central America.\par
From what they could piece together from bits of conversation, the group had been making systematic thefts of American currency. With it they were secretly buying arms, ammunition, and plane parts or bribing dishonest factory workers to steal airplane engines and equipment.\par
North Woods had been chosen as a base of operations because it was so near the seacoast, yet not likely to be subject to interference. The contraband was crated here before being transported to the yacht by the helicopter.\par
"So the packing was the hammering we heard on the sound detector," Joe said to Jezro.\par
Krack overheard the remark. "Yes," he replied, "but our own detector warned us you were gettin' too close, so we stopped work."\par
Encouraged by Krack's bragging, Frank and Joe shot questions at them. Renaldo, they learned, was a notorious South American racketeer. He had met Krack, an unprincipled animal trainer, in the underworld, and had arranged the North Woods deal with him. Krack, in turn, had found Trippek and the others.\par
Krack suddenly gave an uproarious laugh. "You kids got the two grand Renny dropped while he was climbing into the helicopter, but we found a way to get it back through that fat friend of yours. We paid off one of our stooges with it."\par
\i So that was how the telltale money found its way into the Hambleton plant!\i0\par
By this time the racketeers, pleased with the impression they thought they were making on the doomed Hardy boys, answered questions freely. It was Krack and Renaldo who had kidnapped Frank and sent the carrier pigeons.\par
"Where did the first pigeon go?" Joe asked.\par
"North Carolina," said Krack. "Brother of mine lives there."\par
"Did you take the other pigeon from our garage?"\par
Trippek nodded, a pleased grin on his face. He seemed to be aware of the efforts the three Hardys had made to trace the home cote of the pigeons.\par
"Who was the woman who followed me from the post office?" Frank asked.\par
"A friend of mine. Good scout, too. She warned Trip when your brother showed up."\par
"Was Renaldo the one who dropped the dark glasses at our house?" Joe asked.\par
"Yeah. When he found your father wasn't home, he decided to have one of you two kids snatched."\par
"Listen here," one of the men in the background called out. "You've told these kids enough now to hang us all."\par
"They won't be around long," Krack said confidently. "I'll turn out a couple of wolves soon as it's dark. I know that gas they got. Only knocks 'em out a few hours."\par
The three prisoners shuddered at the thought of being torn to pieces by ravening wild beasts. The sun already had set. In a few hours the woods would be cloaked in darkness, the-\par
"Come on!" Krack ordered. "Let's get back to the cabin. I'm going to see if I can get a coded message through to Haxon before we pull out for the islands."\par
The men made sure the boys were securely bound, then disappeared. Frank and Joe struggled furiously at their bonds, but the wires would not budge. They only cut more deeply into their flesh. To keep their minds off the fate awaiting them, the brothers discussed the case with Jezro.\par
"What about the pigeons in the woods?" Frank asked. "Why was one shot, Jezro?"\par
"It wasn't supposed to be. I did that. I didn't know it was one of our birds. But I guess my shootin' days are over. We're goners now," he added despondently.\par
As night descended, the man's terror grew almost to hysteria. He moaned and babbled as though losing his reason. The Hardys called back and forth, to keep up their hopes, though their spirits had never been lower. Any minute now the wolves might be released.\par
Suddenly a distant sound pierced the stillness. The wailing siren! The helicopter was coming! Were the gang making their getaway from their North Woods hideout?\par
The siren was answered by the loud blast of the one located at the gang's cabin. A few minutes later the beams of a searchlight were lighting the sky above the trees.\par
The boys could hear Krack and his gang coming on the run to roll up the canvas camouflage on the landing field. Presently through the trees the boys could see the lights around the rim of the clearing.\par
They strained to look upward as the craft hovered overhead, and watched as it gently touched the ground. As its door swung open, the smugglers rushed to meet the pilot.\par
To the boys' joy and amazement, they saw Fenton Hardy and several state troopers alighting from the chopper.\par
"Don't move, any of you!" came an order from Mr. Hardy which rang through the silent woods.\par
Trippek and Krack stood staring, unbelieving. Then Renaldo sprang toward the lights. If he could plunge the place into darkness, he and his friends might escape.\par
An officer's gun clipped a bit o\'a3 foliage just above the man's head, and the leader of the gang suddenly seemed to change his mind.\par
Then they heard their father demanding angrily what they had done with his sons. A moment later the detective was snipping the wires that bound Joe and Frank. Then, though their arms and legs were cramped, the boys had the supreme pleasure of helping the troopers manacle the criminals and march them to the helicopter. Joe and Frank, with their father and two of the police officers, stayed behind to round up Jezro and the remaining lesser members of the gang, and to tie up the wolves. A police helicopter would return to pick them up later.\par
"Gosh, Dad, you came just in time!" Joe cried gleefully, when the boys had a chance to speak to him alone.\par
"How did you get loose?" Frank asked him.\par
"I was never caught."\par
"What?"\par
\i "I \i0 got Saber before he got me. Then I made my way to Krack's cabin and overheard him talking to Haxon on short wave. He mentioned that the helicopter was hidden at the Beekman farm. Then I got a message through to Sam Radley, who was secretly tailing us all the time to take over if I needed him. I told him to let himself be captured by the gang, while I went to notify the troopers. I even gave him the gas gun to make Krack and his crew think it was I they had nabbed."\par
"So Sam fooled them!"\par
"Right. Fortunately for me, Krack and Jezro didn't know what I looked like. I hurried to get help from the state troopers to raid the old barn and capture the helicopter and the pilot."\par
"What about Haxon?" Frank asked.\par
"I notified the Coast Guard. They seized the yacht and have Haxon in the brig. Which, by the way, solves my mystery of the stolen currency and the smuggled munitions. A list of the thieves and gunrunners was found in Haxon's cabin."\par
"And our mystery is solved, too," Frank said, telling what Jezro had revealed.\par
The Hardys picked their way through the woods to Krack's cabin, where they found and released Sam Radley.\par
What the gangsters had not already told was learned from records found in a desk. Two airplane motors and other stolen equipment were found and brought out of the woods the next day.\par
Solved, also, was one of the questions that had puzzled Frank and Joe ever since the day they had seen the airplane motor in the shack. The engines were taken apart and brought piecemeal from the house where Frank had been imprisoned. A crack mechanic, one of the gang, had reassembled the engines in the forest shack.\par
Bayport buzzed with the news of the Hardys' latest exploit. Many people prophesied that another mystery would soon come their way. It did and was titled \i The Secret of Wildcat Swamp.\i0\par
The following night Mrs. Hardy invited her sons' special friends to a party at their home to celebrate the successful wind-up of the case.\par
Soon the living room was filled with music and chatter. Even Aunt Gertrude, who was serving sandwiches, was feeling mellow.\par
"Thank goodness those cutthroats were caught," she said, proud of her nephews and their father. "Did you get your-our-money back, Chester?"\par
Chet's mouth was filled with a ham sandwich, so he could only nod the good news. Then he swallowed and said, "And my uncle's rifles, too."\par
Mr. Hardy came in to report more good news. The men in the speedboat and the launch had been arrested.\par
"And our pilot friend Jack Wayne was found in Haxon's Caribbean headquarters," he said. "He and some other pilots had been kidnapped with their planes by stowaways and were being held to train pilots for the subversive armies. Wayne's on his way back to Bayport right now."\par
The boys sent up a cheer. When it subsided, the detective went on, "Frank and Joe have been given a reward for their part in the capture of Red Mike, Renaldo, Krack, and Trippek."\par
Again the guests cheered.\par
"What are you going to do with your reward?" Chet asked the Hardys.\par
The brothers grinned. "We'll use some of it to help pay for all of that camping equipment you charged," Joe said.\par
